<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-113-058  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 113 058.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  March 13 1989 n408 p17(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Tapping into the Fortune 50,000 network. (communicationsmanagement) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hayes, Tom.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microcomputer-based network management products can simplify thecommunications planning needs of the Fortune 50,000, which consistof smaller companies in manufacturing, banking, insurance,education, medical and other fields.andP;  These companies face thesame communications problems as the larger firms but must solvethem with fewer resources.andP;  Typically, these firms' areexperiencing greater communications needs, pressure forapplications, and are working with a system composed of variousboxes such as multiplexers, lease and dial modems, small switchesand data service units or channel service units for high-speeddigital links.andP;  Codex Corp's 9300 NMS network management system issoftware that runs on HP's IBM-AT-compatible microcomputer.andP;  Itoffers menu-driven color screens that provide graphicalrepresentations of network events.andP;  It is simple to use, operatingvia a mouse.andP;  It allows management for uptime, device inventoryand maintenance and network planning.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Codex Corp. (products).andO;Product:   Codex 9330 (Computer network software) (usage).andO;Topic:     Communications ManagementNetwork ManagementAutomation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>